{
  "texts": [
    "We first review the definition of symmetric loss functions.",
    "Definition 3 (Symmetric loss function).",
    "A loss functionL is called symmetric if it satisfies, for some constant C, K k=1 L(f (x), k) = C, ∀x ∈ X, ∀f.We then have a guarantee: Theorem 1.",
    "Normalized negative loss function L nn, as specified in Equation (7), is symmetric.Detailed proofs can be found in Appendix B.",
    "The general properties of symmetric loss functions have been well studied, and we refer reader to [45] for more discussions on topics such as classification calibration and excess risk bound.2) NNLFs are robust to label noise: For any loss function L, given a classifier f, the L-risk is defined asR L (f) = E x,y [L(f (x), y)], where E is the expectation operator and its subscript denotes on which the expectation is taken."
  ]
}